Introduction

Laplacian renomalisation group (LRG) is a dimensional reduction technique inspired from physics. The specific heat of a physical system, ie network, can be used to measure the point at which the system transitions from high-dimensional space to a coarse-dimensional space whilst preserving the underlying toplogy of the system.

[1] Villegas, P., Gili, T., Caldarelli, G. et al. Laplacian renormalization group for heterogeneous networks. Nat. Phys. 19, 445–450 (2023). https://doi.org/10.1038/s41567-022-01866-8



## load function required to perform LRG on a network
source(here("core_functions.R"))



1 ER Networks

ER network with 256 vertices

Set the random seed for reproducibility

## Set the random seed for reproducibility.
#set.seed(1234)
## Number of samples
Nits = 500

## Node of nodes
Nv = 256

## Average Degree
K = 30

## Node names
gn = seq(1,Nv,1)

Lmean      = matrix(0,Nv,Nv)
Esample    = list()
Vsample    = matrix(0,Nv,Nv)
Vinvsample = matrix(0,Nv,Nv)

for( i in 1:Nits ){

## ER Graph
gg=random.graph.game(n=Nv, (K*Nv)/2, type="gnm", directed=FALSE)

## Set node names
V(gg)$name = gn

L = get.L(gg)
E = get.eigen(L, only.values=FALSE, inv.vec=TRUE)

Lmean        = Lmean + as.matrix(L)
Esample[[i]] = E[[1]]
Vsample      = Vsample + E[[2]]
Vinvsample   = Vsample + E[[3]]

}

Lmean   = Lmean/Nits  
Emargin = do.call(rbind, Esample)
Emean   = apply(Emargin, 2, mean)
Esd     = apply(Emargin, 2, sd)
Evec    = Vsample/Nits
Evinv   = Vinvsample/Nits

Where does dC/dt cross zero

tt.steps = 1e-2
tt      = tibble(tau=seq(1e-2,1e0, tt.steps))
dc      = dC_dt_test_wrapper(n=Nv, t=tt$tau, e=Emean)
dc.diff = diff(sign(dc))
dc.indx = which(abs(dc.diff)==2)
tau.x   = NA
if( length(dc.indx) > 0 ){ tau.x   = tt$tau[dc.indx] }
print(tau.x)
## [1] 0.24

Calculate graph renormalisation round tau.x

t.lower  = 0.1#tau.x-.15
t.upper  = tau.x


lrg.scan = scan.time(gg=gg, e=E[[1]], v=E[[2]], vinv=E[[3]], L=L, t.lower=t.lower, t.upper=t.upper,
                      complex=FALSE, method="eigen", order=1, n.steps=100, print=0)
## TEST
lrg.ann = anneal.time(gg=gg, L=L, e=E[[1]], v=E[[2]], vinv=E[[3]], 
                      t.lower=t.lower, t.upper=t.upper, cooling_rate=0.85,

## Scan algorithm
indx.best = which.min(lrg.scan$df$jsd)
tau.best  = lrg.scan$df$t[indx.best]

## Annealing algorithm
indx.best1 = nrow(lrg.ann$df)
tau.best1  = lrg.ann$df$new_t[indx.best1]
